@page "/wasm-board"
@rendermode @(new InteractiveWebAssemblyRenderMode(prerender: false))

@using BgDataTypes_Lib
@using BackgammonDiagram_Lib
@using BgDiag_Razor.Components

@*
    Phase 2a feasibility probe — the ONLY job of this page is to prove that
    BackgammonDiagram (BgDiag_Razor → BackgammonDiagram_Lib.RenderSvg) renders
    inside the browser-wasm runtime, with SkiaSharp/QuestPDF/OpenXml present in
    the dependency closure as never-loaded dead weight.

    No filters, no quiz flow, no file picker — one hardcoded board. The render
    runs entirely client-side (prerender:false), so a visible SVG here means the
    native-bundling library closure is WASM-viable. The board data is the
    standard opening position, built via DiagramRequest.Builder exactly as
    BgDiag_Razor's own tests do.
*@

<PageTitle>BgQuiz — WASM board spike</PageTitle>

<div class="container py-3">
    <h1>WASM board spike</h1>

    <p class="text-muted">
        Rendered client-side in WebAssembly via
        <code>BackgammonDiagram_Lib.DiagramRenderer.RenderSvg</code>. If you can
        see the board below, the bundled-native-deps closure is WASM-viable.
    </p>

    <div class="board-container my-3" style="max-width:800px">
        <BackgammonDiagram Request="_request" Options="_options" />
    </div>
</div>

@code {
    private readonly DiagramOptions _options = new();

    // Standard opening position in MOP (mover's-own-perspective) board form:
    // index 0 = opponent bar, 1–24 = points, 25 = on-roll bar; positive = on-roll.
    private static readonly DiagramRequest _request = new DiagramRequest.Builder
    {
        Mop = [0, 2, 0, 0, 0, 0, -5, 0, -3, 0, 0, 0, 5, -5, 0, 0, 0, 3, 0, 5, 0, 0, 0, 0, -2, 0],
        OnRollName = "Player",
        OpponentName = "Opponent",
        Dice = [3, 1],
        CubeSize = 1,
        CubeOwner = CubeOwner.Centered,
    }.Build();
}
